\begin_layout Abstract
Agricultural extension services are generally biased towards men, with male
 extension agents targeting the man within the household.
 In a field experiment among maize-farming households in Uganda, we investigate
 the consequences of this by varying exposure to extension information by
 gender within the household, as well as by varying the gender of the person
 who provides this information.
 We find that targeting women increases their knowledge about improved maize
 management practices, their role in agricultural decision-making, their
 adoption of recommended practices and inputs, production-related outcomes,
 and quantity sold.
 The gender of the person providing information has mixed effects on empowerment.
