\begin_layout Standard
Women provide a lot of work, yet men generally make the decisions.
 While women form a substantial part of the workforce these days, relatively
 few hold executive positions across a range of sectors and industries.
 One extreme example is that, according to Fortune 500's 2019 list, only
 6.6 percent of companies had a woman Chief Executive.
 And while there is an increase in the share of women in middle management
 globally, women are often promoted in positions that involve little strategic
 decisions making, such as human resource departments or communications.
 This problem is even more compelling when considering unpaid work such
 as household care and child care.
 For instance, while women bare the brunt of child care, their voice in
 deciding how many children to have is limited 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "10.1257/aer.104.7.2210"

\end_inset

.
 Economic dependency upon men in the context of strict gender norms means
 that the vast majority of women in developing countries lack the ability
 to make important choices and act upon them in their daily lives.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One route towards increasing women empowerment may be targeting them with
 information.
 The existence of information asymmetries between spouses has been found
 to affect intra-household resource allocation in ways that suggests information
 increases bargaining power 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "AMBLER201552,10.1257/aer.103.3.263,10.1257/aer.99.4.1245,chen2006migration"

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "10.1257/app.20170416"

\end_inset

 find that the share of girls reporting sex against their will dropped by
 close to a third as a result of providing them with, inter alia, information
 on sex, reproduction, and marriage.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "10.1257/app.3.1.1"

\end_inset

 finds that providing new information to adolescent girls – that older men
 are more likely to be infected with HIV – reduced sex with older men.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Information campaigns have several features that determine effectiveness.
 In addition to who is targeted by the information, the source of the informatio
n has also been found to matter.
 Some studies show that information may be more credible if it comes from
 an official source 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "eg."
key "10.1257/app.5.1.104"

\end_inset

.
 Other studies find that information is more effective if one can identify
 more with the person or persons who provide the information 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "doi:10.1146/annurev.soc.27.1.415"

\end_inset

.
 Homophily effects, where women learn more from other women, may be particularly
 important for women empowerment.
 More recently, the behavioral economics literature also started to point
 out the importance of role models, suggesting important non-cognitive impact
 pathways that can be exploited in information campaigns.
 For instance, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "porter2019gender"

\end_inset

 show that successful role models can increase entry in traditionally male
 dominated sectors.
 Role models not only affect the behavior of those that identify with the
 model; they have also been found to influence the behavior of others in
 situations where women are constrained by relationships and social norms
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "10.1162/qjec.2009.124.4.1497"

\end_inset

.
 More in general, role models may facilitate shifts in social norms.
 For instance, a large part of the reduction in fertility as a consequence
 of introducing soap operas in Brazil reported in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "10.1257/app.4.4.1"

\end_inset

 should be attributed the fact that the show projected a very different
 vision of the good life than the one that Brazilians were used to 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "banerjee2012poor"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Also in the context of smallholder agriculture, women work long days on
 the field, yet have little voice in deciding what crops to grow, which
 technologies to use, and how to dispose of the crops 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "magnan2015information,FISHER201582"

\end_inset

.
 However, there are many well-established benefits to empowering women farmers
 in developing countries.
 A more prominent role for women in the farm household has been shown to
 result in more efficient allocations of scarce resources within the household,
 more equitable distributions of the returns to investments in household
 production, and general improvements in welfare and poverty 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "10.1093/wber/lhw011,10.2307/24582373,DEBRAUW2014487"

\end_inset

.
 Involving women in the choice of crops may also lead to more nutritious
 dietary outcomes at the household level 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "doi:10.1111/1468-0084.t01-1-00052,duflo2004intrahousehold"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One important constraining factor is asymmetric information between spouses
 on a range of productivity-enhancing technologies and practices.
 The fact that women possess less knowledge necessarily limits their participati
on in decision-making on agricultural production 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "FISHER201582"

\end_inset

.
 Men rarely discuss agronomic practices or management choices with their
 wives or female partners 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "magnan2015information,FISHER201582"

\end_inset

, and agricultural extension services rarely recognize women in their role
 as agricultural producers 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "doi:10.1111/j.1574-0862.2001.tb00233.x,DOSS20012075"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Reducing information asymmetry related to agriculture between men and women
 by targeting women with information that is presented in an appealing way
 may thus be empowering.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "BENYISHAY2020102380"

\end_inset

 show that men and women learn and retain information about the new technology
