\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the context of smallholder agriculture in developing countries, information
 related to productivity-enhancing technologies and practices is generally
 disseminated though public agricultural extension information systems.
 However, agricultural extension systems are generally biased toward men,
 with information targeted mainly to male members of a farming household
 and in formats that are rarely tailored to female members.
 A recent survey on public service delivery in Uganda found that only 16
 percent of extension agents are women.
 As such, extension information systems fail to recognize gendered power
 dynamics governing intra-household information exchanges and confirm a
 worldview in which women are largely absent from agricultural decision-making
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "DOSS20012075,QUISUMBING2010581"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this paper, we examine ways in which extension services can be designed
 to effectively increase women’s access to informational resources, their
 agency, and their achievements in farming, all of which directly relate
 to women’s empowerment in agriculture.
 Specifically, we conduct a field experiment among 3,600 maize-farming household
s in eastern Uganda to test cognitive and behavioral channels through which
 extension information affects outcomes related to maize management and
 production.
 To test the cognitive channel, we compare outcomes of households where
 the female co-head was included in the target audience to outcomes of household
s where information was targeted to the male co-head alone.
 To test the behavioral channel, we compare outcomes of households where
 a women was included in the dissemination of the information to outcomes
 of households where the information is provided by only a man.
 Our experimental design also allows us to test for the existence of gender
 homophily effects.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The information intervention is implemented as a short video that provides
 viewers with information and recommendations on appropriate input use,
 management practices, and investment strategies that can be followed to
 obtain higher maize yields.
 To test the impact of reducing information asymmetries between spouses,
 we randomly varied who was shown the video within the household.
 This could either be the male co-head alone, the women co-head alone, or
 both co-heads together (the couple).
 Furthermore, three versions of the video were created—one featuring a male
 actor, another featuring a female actor, and a third featuring both actors
 together—with no difference in the information contained in the video.
 Varying the exposure to the actors of different gender in this way allows
 us to test a second hypothesis related to the importance of role models
 to empower women.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We find that targeting women with extension videos has a positive effect
 on different domains of empowerment including their knowledge of agronomic
 practices; participation in agricultural decision-making especially on
 the adoption of recommended practices and inputs; increased maize yields,
 quantities and sales by women.
 However, portraying women as successful farmers and role models in the
 screening produces mixed results in these domains.
 Further, results suggest that role-model effects work differently for women
 and men.
 
\end_layout

